### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Google Maps and other highway and street GPS services have replaced what? Choices:  A: united states B: mexico C: countryside D: atlas E: oceans<n>Output:		The choices are A: united states,B: mexico,C: countryside,D: atlas, and E: oceans.<n>The correct answer is A: united states<n>So the final answer for this instruction is united states<n><n>Input:The city was divided into four parts in the early twenties. A map of the city in 1922 shows that about 80 percent of the city was white and about 20 percent was black. In 2000, the white population was 50 percent of the city's population while the black population made up 45 percent.<n><n>Output: A map of the city shows that the white population was 20 percent of the city.<n>The number of the black population increased by 55 percent from 1922 to 2000.<n>So the final answers is 55%<n><n>Input: A map of the town in 1925 shows that about 78 percent of the residents were black and 12 percent were white, the percentage of blacks decreased significantly at a later date. As a result, the white population grew at a higher rate than what ?<n>Output: In the given map it is shown that the white percentage  of the town is 12 which was in 1924. Therefore 78% of the population is black.<n><n>After some time the percentage of blacks is increased. So, the percentage of black decreased the same at  which the  percentage of whites increased.<n>That means the white population increased by 2/3th of what the % blacks decreased at that time.<n><n>Solution:<n><n>78% of the town percentage is black.<n>78 x 2/3 = <<78/3=88.88>>88.88% of the town is black.<n>Therefore whtie  population increased by 0.888888/3 = <<88.88/3=29.63>>29.63%.<n>So the final answer it's 29.63%<n><n><n>Input: A population of 660,000 people lives in a city. This number is decreasing at 28% per year. How much will that population decrease in four years

How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Too many people want exotic snakes. In the mathematical expression:<n><n>1 + 2 + 3 + 4 +...... + n<n><n>n is the last natural number. So, n would be 150.<n><n>Therefore, sum = 150<n><n>### Step:<n>Step 1: Make a note of the given values.<n><n> Step 2: Add the values in an expression to get more than 1, then add one.<n> Step 3: Write the result of this operation and repeat the process.<n> Step 4: Keep doing this process until there is not more than one.<n> Step 5: Get the sum of remaining values.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What state is the John Davis  Lodge toll road found in? Choices:  A: new jersey B: eastern united states C: good repair D: connecticut E: arizona<n>Output:		A. It is in New Jersey<n>You should be able to answer all the questions given for practice below.<n>For the remaining questions, show your thought process in completing the problem, and also let me know if you get any errors.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:You can hear testimony of how spirituality changes lives when you do what? One number is four more than the other. Find the two numbers.<n>Output: Let the numbers be x and y.<n>x+y=13<n>(x-4)+y=13<n><n>x+y-4=13-4<n><n>x+y=9<n><n>x=9-y<n><n>So the final answer of two numbers is x=9 and y=4

How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Sam went to Paris where he ordered a blowfish at a sushi place. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Where is likely to have a lot of fire extinguishers? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:They checked the weather one more time during the flight, they were on their way to paradise and wanted it to what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:The camper looked up at the vast night sky, it left him feeling mighty what? Each chair will have x number of students. <n> Output: The value of x varies depending on the number of people in the classroom. If there are 15 there are 7 chairs (there are five chairs, with two pairs of a student per pair and no chair for one student). If there are 5 there are three chairs, with one pair of students sharing a chair and one student without a chair. If there is one student, they have 45 chairs. <n>So there need to be 7 chairs for there to be 22 students in a large classroom with 6 chairs<n><n>Input: The temperature in the garden today is 69 degrees Fahrenheit and 8 degrees below the high for the day and 2 degrees above the low.<n>Output: -30 degrees below the high and 1 degree above the low.<n>The output will be 31-30=1.<n><n>Input: I love my dog and she love me.<n>Output: I love my dog. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:I am looking to buy honey right from an apiary, where should I go? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. Choices:  A: frustration B: being annoyed C: delays D: irritation E: out of order<n>Output:		They were annoyed at what they had to suffer<n>Since they were irritated they had a feeling of annoyance, being annoyed.<n>So the final ans is annoyed<n><n>Input: Jesse said "I have a large bowl of ice cream" She meant she had a quantity of ice cream that was equal to the amount of ice cream in a large bowl. Lili's memories<n>Output: None of these choices apply to Lili. <n>The first choice says the things in Lili' s life and none of these are these in Lili' s case.<n>In the 2nd choice, it says Lili's life but they don't apply to the things happening here.<n>3rd choice talks about Lili's experiences, that doesn't apply to Lili as we can tell her experiences are about her in the options but that doesn't describe her things, life, or feelings and so on.<n>4th choice is Lili' s feelings but those aren't in any of the option neither is the final choice for her memories.<n>So since none of them apply to Lili' s life, <n>they aren't doing anything to describe her life.<n><n>Input: Tom took five apples from the pile. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:The child pounded his mitt in excitement while enjoying his first game in the bleachers where? So, the answer should be B<n><n>Input:<n>The cat chased a mouse through the dark hall, down the hall, and into the kitchen? Choices:<n>1.A: behind the house 2.B: down the hall 3.C: behind the mailbox 4.D: through the hall 5.E: in the alley<n>Output: The cat chased the mouse through the dark hall and into the kitchen. So the answer should be B(or the hall)<n><n>Input:<n>A frog jumped from one lily pad to the next. It hopped the green lily pads and green grass. Choices for the number of lily pads it jumped between: 15 55 155 555<n>Output: A frog jumped from lily pad to lily pad that have green grass between them. So the answer should 55<n><n>Input: In her car, Linda had 3 books to read, 5 puzzles to work on, and 23 CDs to listen to. If Linda could only  read,  work on puzzles, and listen to CDs equally,  how many more books did she have than puzzles?<n>Output: The answer should be 11(number of the books she had).<n>The equation looks like: n-n-n=(1*3)+(-1*5)+(1 *23) => n - n - n = 15 - 5-23 => n = 15+5+23 => n =11<n>So the ans is 11.<n><n>Input:<n>In a room with brown, red, gray, white, and yellow chairs, 17 people are seated so that each chair is occupied by an even number and is chosen randomly in sequence. <n>How many different arrangements can this group of chairs be arranged,  where people choose their seats randomly and seating is not affected by precedent arrangement?<n><n>Output:<n>There are 6! (6*5*4*3*2*1 ) - 1(because there no 1st person who can occupy a chair) = 2184 combinations.<n>So the ans is A<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. The answer is 60.<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:An electronics store had things damaged from the rain, where should these things be stored? Choices:  A: large city B: strip mall C: building D: shopping mall E: aquarium<n>Output:		If the damaged items are at the aquarium, they can find a home with <<100*65>>100 fish and <<100*100>>100 turtles.<n><n>Input:What is an equation of a line that has a slope of -2 and a y intercept of 200? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:A water spout was seen in the ocean off the coast of what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:When I was home, I was comfortable. Choices:  A: theatre B: fairgrounds C: friend's house D: show E: casino<n>Output:		Choices are fairgrounds or show.<n><n>A and E are not an option, because they are not entertainment. <n>B and C are not an option, becasue a fairgrounds does not have a theatre.<n>Finally, if you went to a fairgrounds, you could go to a theater there, and the final answer is theatre.<n><n><n><n><n>### Instruction:Analyze these instructions.<n><n>Input:What is the probability of rolling a 1 on one die or on two dice?<n>Output: We will compute the probability of rolling a one on one die, which is one fourth. On two dice, there are four possible combinations of a one, so the probability of getting a 1 on two dice is one fourth to the power of four. <n> <n>One way to think about probablity is: we use the sample space (the set of all all possible outcomes) but with two dice, we can determine all of the possible combinations: each of the four sides of one die and the four results from the roll of the other die.<n>Therefore, we have:<n> <n>P(dice 1== 1 and dice 2== 1) = P(dice 1 == 1)/P(dice 2 == 1), then, P(dice 2) = 1/(P(dice 4)).<n>So, we get:<n><n>P(one dice 1== 1)/P(two dice one 2== 1))<n>= 1/4<n>= 0.25<n>and the final answer is 1/4.<n><n>### Instructions:Answer the following problems in your own words.<n>### How could you change the input and output of the instructions below?<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Where are all participants likely to need sports equipment? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. If its destination was 220 miles from its starting point, how long did it take it to get there?<n>Output: It is never flying in a straight path.<n>Therefore, after increasing its speed, it makes 60 x 2 = <<60*2=120>>120 miles in the same time period that it would take it on its original path with only 60 miles.<n>Then, at 120 miles, it doubles its speed. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What do people who are speech therapists do? Choices:  A: make music B: believe in god C: give speeches D: complete sentences E: build houses<n>Output:		Speech therapists create and understand languages by providing therapy to people who have speech disorders. <n>Answer (1 Point): The answer here is D.<n><n>Input: What are the numbers that are divisible by 2, 3, and 4?<n>Output: All integers that can be evenly divided by 2, 4, or 3 are divisible by 6. Only 2 and 4 are prime numbers, and only an even number can be evenly divided.<n>Answer ( 1 Point ): 62, 64, 66, 68, 70, 72, 74, 76, 78, 80, 82, 84, 86, 88, 90, 92, 94, 96<n><n>Input: How much coffee did each person pour?<n>Jordan poured 17 ounces<n>Spencer poured 17 oz<n>Trevor poured 25 ounces<n>Andrew poured 5 ounces<n>Kevin poured 5 ounce<n>Oscar poured 7 ounces<n>Frank poured 9 ounces<n>Sarah poured 9 ounce<n>Mike poured 10 ounce<n><n>Output: In this case, the answer is F. The total is more than all the amounts from each person.<n>Output: The total is over 100 ounces.<n>Answer (1 Point ):The total is more than 663 ounces, which is not a multiple of 10.<n><n>Input: For more practice, use your calculator to solve the following problems.<n>Output: 3/4  * 4 =4<n>1/2 * 5 =2.5<n>Output: Here we use the method of long division on the calculator to get a close approximation to 10/3<n>10/3=3.33…(rounded to 3.3).<n>We are able to approximate using only 6 digits and the calculator.<n>If we were able to do 16 digits, we would get a better approximation, 3.333333…<n><n>### Questions to answer in the REPL/Console, like the previous

Choices:  A: say thank B: smile C: looking for D: get more E: show appreciation<n>Output:		2 times the answer is the answer<n>Saying thank is 50% of ANSWER.<n>So, when we get something, we<n><n>(  50% of A - B  )+(  50% of C  )+(  54% of D  ) =  The ANSWER<n><n><n>*<n><n>*<n><n><n><n>*<n>#<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:The kids had been having fun all day, there was now a what? Choices:  A: wild ride B: need for rest C: a massive bear D: playing marbles E: constructing<n>Output:		A: Massive bears, not marbles<n>

Necessity<n>Necessity means that something cannot or must be done, and nothing can replace it.<n>So I think "A" cannot be the answer since talking and communicating can be alternative activities to replace chatting in class. Answers<n>The answer choices are irrelevant. <n>All the answers are "answers".<n>I'm confused how B can be an answer choice. <n>In our classroom, we just sit and listen to the lectures. Love<n>I choose this one.<n>Love means that you do favors or something of that nature because you can't live without it.<n>If you don't chat with friends in class, you are not loved. <n>So the best answer is "Love".<n><n>### Question 5.<n>#### E. Nothing<n>"F" is the correct answer. <n>According to the definition, it means that you are doing something you like. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:If I wanted to thank someone for saying I have done a good job, what would I do? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:james loved the stars. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:The human looked down longingly as he sat in the orbiting space station, what did he miss? What is the number?<n>Output:There are two choices, if we take first equation then AX - (B + 9) = C where A,B and C are positive integers And if we take the second equation, then A(B - 1) - 9A + 3 = C where A, B, and C are positive integers.<n>Now, if first equation is assumed and it is equated with second then (3 - B) /9 = A, But we know that 9 is common in both equations and also (3 - B) ≡ A (modulus 9). If both sides are divisible by 3 and the difference between them is equivalent to A modulus 9, then 7(modulus 9) ≡ A ( mod). The difference between the two sides of the equation is 3 and as we all know 3 ≡ 1 mod 9, then the value of A is 4, so our answer is 4<n><n>Input

How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What might a satisfied person do? Choices:  A: board ship B: grocery shop C: cross street D: feel happy E: shout at<n>Output:		A and B - These are the things a Satisfied person Does<n><n>Input:A person has some apples and oranges. How far is it from the starting point to where the total distance is?<n>Output: Total Distance = 25 - 5 + 5 + 5 = 25 + 10 = >> <<25+10=35>> = 35 meters

How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What will happen to your knowledge with more learning? Choices:  A: headaches B: bigger brain C: education D: growth E: knowing more<n>Output:		Choice C is correct. More learning causes your brain to grow. The brain is like a muscle. When you exercise a muscle, you cause more blood to go there. The blood carries oxygen and nutrients, which are needed for the brain to grow. Without exercise, the brain cells wither away and die.<n>So the final option is (C) education<n><n>* * * <n><n>Please find the attached file with the working in detail...<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:The mother was worried about all the spills, so she bought a rug for under the what? How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:A student wants to hear what the professor is saying, what does he do? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What does someone need to do to begin creating art? Choices:  A: relax B: controversy C: pleasure D: frustration E: needs theater<n>Output:		A: relax and B: please<n><n><n>Input:A book of the Bible is called the Psalms. The author is David. He wrote the Psalms in Israel under King Saul.<n>Output:Israel and king saul<n><n>Input:What do the following words start with? Choices:<n>1.  m 2.  in 3.  b 4.  r 5.  d 6.  p 7.  f<n>Output:1.  b and 4.  d<n>

Her sister runs 50 % of the total miles she run. If her sister run 20 miles, then how many miles is Jane from her sister?<n>Output: Jane is 4/10 = <<4/10=0.4>>0.4 of her sister's distance.<n>Her sister runs 1/2 = <<1/2=2.2>>2.2 of the distance Jane run in 1 total mile she runs.<n>However, her sister ran 20 miles to begin with, so to reach that distance, she ran 20 x 0.4 = <<20*0.4=8>>8 miles.<n>Now we want to know how many miles Jane ran.<n>She ran <<20-8>>20 - 8 = <<20-8=12>>12 miles to reach <<20*0/2=20/2>>20/2 distance from her sister.<n>Thus, Jane ran 12/2 = <<12/2=7>>7 miles to get to her sister.<n>So the final answe is 7

Choices:  A: garbage can B: military C: jewelry store D: safe E: airport<n>Output:		the woman was heading to the airport if she only had a drawstring bag, and there are only one of choice A, B, and E. The choices C and D are the same, so there are only two choices, so C must be the woman's destination.<n><n>### 96. Question:<n><n>You might have seen a mall or large department store named JCPenney in a city. JCPenney is an American department store chain operated by JCPenney Company and is headquartered in Plano, Texas. JCPenney started with just one store in Kemmerer, Wyoming in 1902. After J.C. Penney passed away in 1971, the company continued to grow. It has over 1000 locations in both states and Canada. This is why the JCPenney is a large chain, and it is one of the most well-known department stores in North America.<n><n>### Instruction:<n><n>JCPenney has a large number of products. You will be shown a different product of JCPenney. There will be only one product shown on the screen.<n><n>You can add as many times as you want to the value of the product. <n>If you want to add values more than once, write the previous number and repeat.<n><n>The answer is the final total of this product.<n><n>After you have entered your answer, a picture will be shown that resembles the product.<n>You will win the number on the products if your answer is correct.<n><n>If you enter the number incorrectly, the game will be over, and you will lose the number.<n><n>### Example:<n><n>Input: This product is 14. It was worth $90. You can add to this any amount you want. It was the right product.<n>Output: The new value of this product is 14 x 9 = <<14*9=126>>126, then the final value of the product is 126<n>Choices: $35 $12 $45 $80<n><n>### 101. Question:<n><n>A man in a room was given four tasks.<n><n>**Task 1** - You must have two more coins than me.<n>**Task 2** - Your value is smaller than mine
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Where do you put your grapes just before checking out? Choices:  A: mouth B: grocery cart C: super market D: fruit basket E: fruit market<n>Output:		You should put the grapes in super market to save it from spoiling for a longer time.<n>The fruit baskets go to homes while their contents are about to spoil. In a supermarket, the contents usually last longer.<n><n><n>A = wrong<n>B = wrong<n>C = wrong<n>D = wrong<n>E = right<n><n><n>Input: How will your teacher answer this question: Which book should I take to read in school? Choices:  Book 1: The Count of Monte Cristo Book 2: Gone With the Wind Book 3: Anna Karenina Book 4: Wuthering Heights Book 5: Pride and Prejudice <n>Answer: All other answers are wrong.<n>You choose The Count of Monte Cristobook to read in school, because it is a classic American literature.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. Therefore, the answer is advisory.<n><n>Input: Three boxes, A, B, and C, are made by a factory. Boxes A and B have 9 green marbles and 3 blue marbles. Box A costs $2 more than Box B. Box C contains exactly twice as many green marbles as blue marbles and costs $4 less than Box A. If Box B contains one more blue marble than Box C, what is the cost in dollars of Box B relative to Box A?<n>Output: Let's use the prices of the boxes to calculate relative price of boxes B and C.<n>So the relative price of B and C are:<n>Box A: $$A \times 10$$<n>Box B: $$ \frac{B}{B-A}$$<n>BoxC: $$\frac{C}{C-A}$$<n>$$\begin{aligned} \frac{B}{1} & \geq \frac{C}{3} \\ \frac{B}{C+1} & \geq B \end{aligned}$$<n>$$\begin {aligned}\frac{B}{3} & \geq B \\ \frac{4B}{9B + 3} & \geq 3 \end{aligned}$$ This is the same as<n>$$\frac{4B}{B+4} & \geq 0$$ Therefore a, b and c must satisfy $$\frac{4}{4+4}+\frac{9BC+2}{9B+3} \geq 0$$ and we get $$ \frac{3}{2} \geq \textstyle\frac{|b|}{|c|} + 0$$<n>So relative price of B and to A is 3/2.<n>Therefore B is three times as costly as A.<n><n>Input: If 49 x + 5 = 4y, and 7 x + 1 = z, then 7 x + z = and

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:How does getting paid feel? Choices:  A: income tax B: satisfaction C: sorrow D: ocean E: bill collectors to happy<n>Output:		Income tax feels like sorrow.<n>```<n><n>```<n><n>```{<n>    "title":"Example 10",<n>    "problem":"Input: A man has 2 cakes, 1 pancakes, and 1 biscuit. How many baked foods are there in all?",<n>    "answer":"There are 2 + 1 + 1 = <<2+1+1=4>>4 types of baked foods",<n>    "instructions":"Answer the question."<n>}<n>```<n><n><n><n>### Example 3<n><n>```{<n>  "title":"Example 3",<n>  "problem":"A clown has 3 balloons and 8 hats. How many hats does he have in all?",<n>  "choices": [<n>    { "option": "\u2219\u2026\u2219" },<n>    { "option" : 8 }<n>  ],<n>  "answer_choice":0<n>}<n>```<n>This one is trickier than others.<n><n>### Example of 9<n><n>```{<n>"title":"Example 9",<n>"question":"John had 2 cups of water. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Where do bees congregate with red flowerS? How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:To learn must have the right book, to work efficiently what must one have? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Where do you buy tickets at a ticket booth for games/ Choices:  A: train station B: cathedral C: metro station D: fairgrounds E: amusement park<n>Output:		A and D, B and E, C and C, and A and E as a combination.<n>So the final answers are: A, B, C, A and E<n><n>### Problem:Find all the 5 letter words you can spell using the 6 letters in the word 'MUSIC' (no repeats allowed)<n>Output:<n>Music, musik, mucis, mucix.<n><n>Input: I walk to a friend’s house, which is 4 blocks west of my house. The next block farther, to the west, has a store called “Jim’s Place.” I pass it on the way home. How many blocks am I from home?<n>Output: The distance I walk to the west is 4 + 1 = <<4+1=5>>5.<n>The distance I walk to the east is 1 + 1 = <<1+1=2>>2.<n>Thus, I am 5 – 2 = <<5-2=3>>3 blocks from home.<n>So the final Answer is Three<n><n>Input: Mr. Gumbo has 8 black licorice alls, which weigh 10.3 ounces. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What is the hope of playing sports without competition? Choices:  A: running B: have fun C: balls touch D: winning E: get tired<n>Output:		There is no hope of playing sports without a competitor.<n>So the final Answer 'is' A<n><n>Input: The answer is correct. How many girls and boys are there? The skeleton of humans can be divided into the skull, chest, pelvis and the rest of the body known as the appendicular skeleton.<n>The appendicular skeleton includes all bones except the skull.<n>It includes the arms that are grouped with the shoulder girdle of the skeleton in what is known as the Axial and Appendicular Skeleton.<n>So the correct answers are D:\ and E:<n>So the final answer should be: D:\ and E:\<n><n>Input:A small town has 6 doctors, 5 lawyers, and 8 dentists. The city council is considering the placement of a new hospital. The hospital will provide a total of 30 medical beds, 25 beds for dental clinic patients, and 35 beds for law clinic patients. After adding the beds, the hospital must provide a total of one bed for every 2 dentists, 3 doctors, and 15 lawyers in the town. How many dentists are there in the town?<n>Output: The total number of dentists in the town is a solution to the following equation:<n><18>2 * <2>3 + <25>1 + <15>1 = <<18*2+25+15=48>>48 dentists.<n>Now, we need to find the dentists among the doctors and lawyers:<n><6>1 * <5>1 + <3>1 + <8>3 + <2>3 + <<25>1+15+1>48 = <<6*5+3+8*3+2*2+25>1+48=65>>65 dentists.<n>Therefore, after accounting for the dentists among the lawyers and doctors there are 65 dentists in the town.<n>So the final answers should be: 6 + 65 dentists = 71 and 91
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:James needed a garage because he spent a lot of money on what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What would children do if they are bored? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. They should already see you every day<n>E is not a problem. The correct answer is never: E is not the correct answer.<n>C is definitely not correct. If someone always wants something, a beer will never be the correct answer.<n>B is not the correct answer either. If someone always wants to be understood by their peers, then they will be beer<n><n>input:The incorrect answer is definitely:<n>1) A.<n>2) C.<n>3) B.<n>4) D.<n><n><n>### Exercise 1:Create a program to print the factors of a given number.<n>For example, say you put in 120, then the factors would be: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 10, 12, 15, 20, 30, and 60.<n><n>### Examples For Exercise 1<n><n>  Enter any positive integer, say 120:<n>Factor 120<n>1 2 3 4 5 6 10 12 15 20 30 60<n><n>  Enter a negative integer, say -120:<n>Negative integers don't have any factors!<n><n>  Enter a non-positive integer, say -800:<n>Negatives and zero don't have any positive factors!<n><n>  How do you define the term "prime factorization" in plain English?<n>Factorization occurs when all of the factors are either 1, the number itself, or one of the numbers it was made up of. Prime factorization occurs when you only end up factoring 1 or itself.<n><n>### Helpful Links and Documentation<n>* https://www.programiz.com/c-programming/examples/c<n>   
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:The little girl was raised selfish, she didn't even care when she was doing what? Choices:  A: crack B: antipathy C: being mean D: disinterest E: unfeeling<n>Output:		Crack C<n><n>Input: There were two sisters who were called by the names Alice and Laura. Laura was the older sister, and Alice was only three years old. The difference between their ages was twice the age of Alice. If Alice was still three years old, how old was Laura?<n>Output: Difference between ages of 3 Alice and 5 Laura = 8<n>If Alice was still three, 8 years after her birth.<n>Laura was 5 years older = 3 + 8 = <<3+8=11>>11 years older = 5<n>So the final answer for her will be 5 - 3 = <<5-3=2>>2<n><n>Input: In the story of Tom Sawyer, what does Huckleberry Finn have to do with Tom Sawyer and his gang of truant boys? Choices: A. Steal food B. Pretend to throw rocks C. Go to the cemetery D. Go to war<n>Output: B. Pretend  to throw rocks<n><n>---<n>_For more questions from_ "Instructions:Answer the following multiple choic… https://t.co/58Bv7Fvk0r" https://t.co/%mzFdJJKd8S<n>---<n><https://github.com/abhilashtotwits/instructions_answer_the_following_multiple_choice_questions/issues/4><n>

What digit does 73,809 have?<n>Output:73,806<n>The number 73,000 has 7 ones, 0 twos, and 0 threes, so it is 73,0 = 730.<n><n>Input: 4 + 2 =6<n><n>Output:Yes<n><n>Input: 20 = 2<n><n>Output: Yes<n><n>Input: -10/2 = - 5<n><n>Output: Yes since you multiply what is negative 1 times 2 which is negative<n><n>Input: -2 - -5 = 1<n><n>Output: Yes, since you multiply negative 2 times a negative a negative.<n><n>Input: (2 + 3) + 4<n><n>Output: 9<n><n>Input: -5 – 9<n><n>Output: – 4<n><n>Input:-5 – 9 = - 4<n><n>Output:(not equal to)<n><n>Input: (5 -2) ÷ 5 = -1/2<n><n>Output: (not equal to)<n>Since you cannot do division when the numerators are different<n><n>Input:4 - 6/3 = 4<n><n>Output(not equal to)<n>You cannot divided by zero<n><n>Input:64 - 28/ 7 = 8<n><n>Output:(not negative)<n>You cannot negate a number you can multiply it by -1<n><n>Input:6/ (7 * -2) = 5/11<n><n>Output:(not positive)<n><n>Input:24/2<n><n>Output:(division by zero)<n><n>Input:10 * 5/10 = 5/5 = 1<n>In the given example, you have 10, times 5/10 this means that<n>5 is a fraction and the other 10 is the denominator or the bottom<n>number, and you can go ahead and cancel that out because is the<n>same number, you have 0/5 that's not equal to.<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Where would a ticket help you to get to a different country? Choices:  A: train station B: baseball stadium C: lottery D: movie E: bus<n>Output:		The answer is A.<n><n>Input: A bus carrying 500 people leaves the station and travels for 5 miles. A second bus carrying 400 people leaves the same station and travels 2 miles. How far from the station are both buses?<n>Output: 3.5 miles apart.<n>Solution: The first bus went 5 miles and the second 2 miles, so they are 5 miles apart. Since there were 900 people on both buses, divide 900/2 = <<900/2=450>>450 by 5 = <<900d/2=455>>455 since both buses split from the same station. So, 455/2 = <<455/2=227>>227 people got off their bus at the first stop and 227 + 450 = <<227+450=677>>677 had to wait. 677 passengers divided by 2 = <<677/2=338>>338 got on the bus on the next stop, and 338 × 5 = <<338*5=1690>>1690 remain at the bus station or on the bus. 1690 - 900 = <<1690-900=790>>790 people made the trip overall, so they will continue to travel for 790/2 = <<790/2=395>>395 more miles until they reach their destination, where they will have to unload 790 + 395 = <<790+395=1185>>1185 people.

How many hours did it take him to take care of the woodpile?<n>Output: Total time: 333/3 + (13/12) (3*1) = <<333/3+(13/12)*(3*1)= >>333/3+4 = <<3333/12==28 4/5 of 28==251/5 of 25 =~25 >>25.<n>He took 28/1/16 = <<28/16==1.6667>> about 1 and 2/3 hours.<n>So, the final answer is 1 and 2//3<n><n>Input:A rectangular baggage carrier can be divided into 6 equal sections. How many triangular bags can load the carrier?<n>Output: There was 6 - 4 = <<6-4=2>> of the carrier to begin with.<n>With each additional bag, 2 - 2 = <<2-2=0>> section is removed.<n>So, the answer is 6 - 4 - 2 = <<6-4-2=0>> 0 triangular bags.<n>So the final Answer is 0.<n><n>Input:There are 8 chairs and 4 tables in a room. If 8 tables make 7 chairs, and 4 tables make 3 chairs, then how many chairs  are there in the room?<n>Output: There were 8 - 8/4 = <<8-8/4=10/2>> chairs.<n>There were 4 - 4/4 = <<4-4/4=1>> tables.<n>Therefore, the answer is 8 - 8 - 4 + 1 = <<8-8-4+1>> 3 chairs.<n>So, the Answer is 3 chairs<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:They wanted to eat at home but the cupboards were barren, so they had to go what? Choices:  A: cook dinner B: eat C: go back to work D: make food E: get food<n>Output:		They had to go <<make>>make food.<n>They wanted to eat at <<home>>home but the cupboards were <<barren>>barren, so they had <<to go>>to go what? <<choices:A: cook dinner B:  eat C: go back  to work D:  make food E: get >><n>So the final answer after fixing all the grammar and spelling is D<n><n>Input: There are 63 students in the English class. The English teacher says, “One third of my students get As, one third get Bs, and one third get Cs. If you take my students who get Cs together with my students who get As, we get 15.” How many students in the English class get As?<n>Output: So that answer is <<15+15+15=45>>45.<n>Half of 63 is <<63/2=31>>31.<n><<One third of that is>>27<n>So half of that answer is 27 + 31 = <<27+31=58>>58.<n>There are 58 students who get either A, B, or C.<n>Of those, there are 15 Bs (1/3 of 58).<n>So the answer is 45 and 15, or <<45+15=60>>sixty.<n>So the final 70<n><n>Input:How many gallons of water were there? Choices: 100 gallons 200 gallons 300 gallons 400 gallons 500 gallons<n>Output: The amount of gallons is 400<n>So the final answer 400<n><n>## <n><n>## Instruction:Answer the above questions on your own.
