There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Some stores trick women to buy products, the sales make it seem like if you buy more you what? Choices:  A: get money B: pay money C: go shopping D: lose money E: save money<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input: Choose the letter that has the opposite meaning of the word before it.  Choice: A. Adopt  B. Aid  C. Ability  D. Opportunity  E. Boundary  F. Oppose  G. Dual <n>Output:  A <n><n>Input: A certain bird can fly 45 feet, or 25 yards in one minute. How far can a bird fly in 1.5 hours??<n>Output: 45*1.5 = <<45*1.05=67.5>>67.5 yards<n><n>Input: If we started with 75 and added 2 more to that than we started with, which one?<n>Output:18<n><n>Input: If you have 56, and the number you double it and put your shirt on, which one? 19 and 56<n>Output:56<n><n>Input: A. Aid  B. Adopt  C. Ability A.<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. Choices:  A: ordering dog food online B: avoid eye contact C: feel guilty D: fall asleep E: blush<n>Output:		Blushing is the only common sign<n><n>Instruction: Answer all questions given below.<n>Q1: If x and y are positive integers such that (2x + y) ÷ (x - y) = 12, which of the following must be true?<n>     A: x is evenly divisible by y but not vice versa.<n>     B: the quotient (y ÷ x) is evenly divisible on x's but not the reverse.<n>     C: x and y are odd integers.<n>     D: y is evenly divisible to x but not the reverse. <n>Instruction:If we had x more y then z<n>Q2: x + 2y = 0<n>     A: x must be greater than 1.<n>     B: x must be greater or equal to 0.<n>     C: the absolute value of x is greater than 2.<n>     D: the absolute value of y must be greater than 2. <n><n>Instruction:What is a common way to check the temperature outside when you're standing in a store?<n><n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Everybody has a little bit of creativity, but only a few lucky ones get to do what for a living? Choices:  A: sew B: create art C: express yourself D: sing and dance E: write<n>Output:		A = sew; B = express yourself; C = create art; D = sing and dance; E = write<n>So the final answer must be express yourself

The phrase comes from the idea that the other side of a fence was the part that you were most envious of. This idea is referenced in John F. Kennedy’s inaugural address. His words included: “I do not believe that any of us would exchange places with another;” meaning that we wanted to improve, rather than just accepting the way things are. So, to be on the “other side of the fence”, would mean that you were better off, than the person who is looking at you. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:He curled up and tried to fall on his shoulder so his arm or what wouldn't take the hit? Choices:  A: leg B: garment C: torso D: body E: road<n>Output:		The torso<n><n>Input: She has a friend who will give her $100 in week’s time, if she can promise to give him $500 when $200 is due. He gives her the money in a week. How much does she have at the end, after her friend has paid up?<n>Output: The friend has a 500/200 = <<500/2=5>>5-day payment plan, so her friend is giving her $100 per day (for 5 days). She will need some start up cash in week one. She is now out $100, and can expect an additional $500 in 7 weeks.<n>Her savings (with what she started with) after week seven will be (600 - 100 + (500/7)) = <<600-(100+50/7)>>6+(25/7)x7. So after 7 weeks she has + (6+(25/1)x7) = <<13+(25/7=3.09)>>3 weeks of cash (525) + 500 = 1025.<n><n>Input: 12. Which of the following is a good estimate for the value of 7! ≈ 5040?<n><n>Output: 7! ≈ (2 x 4 x 3 x 2 x 1) = 24<n><n>Input:  <n><n>36. How many different ways can 10 people be seated around a square table so that no 2 have equal distance between them?<n><n>Output:  <n><n>Total possible number of seats around the table is 14 as<n>There are 14 unique ways to arrange 10 persons around 10 places.<n>As a result, there are 14C 10 ways to sit 10 persons around the table so that the difference between any to pairs is at least one.<n>There are  14!/4!/2! ways to choose the row and column (or rows or columns) for each person and two unique orders for each row or row/column pair, for a total of 342/114 ways to arrange 7 people around a 6-space table.<n><n>

How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Where you have finished a conversation with a person what do you say? So, the answer to this question is no.<n><n><n><n>Input : The second instruction is to take the sweater that matches one sock.<n><n>Output: Based on the previous answer, since the pair of socks are identical, he would only have brown socks. So the answer to this question should be no.<n><n><n>Input:<n>The first instruction is to accept both red pairs of slippers and take both red pairs of socks.<n><n>Output: His answer to the question should be no. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Where would you put a computer other than a desk? Choices:  A: apartment B: table C: school D: office E: house<n>Output:		B. C or C would be incorrect.<n>A, B, or C would also be incorrect.<n>"In general, the computer will live on a desk in office or apartment."<n>"In most office buildings, the computer lives in the office."<n>Therefore, you should choose either A or B.<n><n>Input:A: apartment B: office C: school D: house E: desk<n>Output:The computer lives on a desk in the office, but most computers are not on desks in the classroom.<n>So, you should choose C, since school is different from an office.<n><n>Input:Choose one of these:<n>A: I am sad. I am not sad.<n>B: I am not sad. I am not upset I am not happy.<n>C: I like it. I dislike it.<n>D: I like it. It makes me happy.<n>E: I don’t like it. I am not happy. I like sad music. I prefer sad movies.<n>Output:A or B. Most people are unhappy or upset; the two alternatives, are not a sad person.<n>In A, C, and E, you like the thing; in B, you are not happy with the thing.<n>In C, you like or don’t like the thing; in A, you are happy or sad.<n>In D, you feel “happy” or “sad” about something; that is the thing that makes you happy. But, there may be other things that may make you happy.<n>The person would be unhappy. If the person liked it, there would be nothing wrong.<n>The person may not like it, or may be happy about it.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Society cannot exist without numbers.   They only rise up in what sort of spaces? Choices:  A: population B: populated area C: create government D: group of people E: make person sick<n>Output:		A The number of inhabitants of a place.<n>So the final option is A<n><n>

Choices:  A: fire B: solar energy C: sun D: house E: coal or wood<n>Output:		The heat source, fire, burns wood, coal, or other materials to create a source of heat.<n>Pick from column A: Fire as the oldest heat source on earth.<n>There is two choices in column B: solar energy, which is the sun's heat that reaches earth and solar panels are used to harness that heat to run appliances and cars, or coal, which is the most used heat source on earth and 16 of the top 20 countries in the world use coal to produce electricity.<n>Pick from options in column C: A: solar energy B: coal C: fire.<n>In Column C, solar energy is a better choice of heat sources, compared to coal and fire.<n>Pick from option in column D: A: solar energy, B: fire, C: coal.<n>Pick A: solar energy which can meet the requirement of a house for the best choice.<n>Pick from colums E: All of the Above, or None of the Above.<n>You can choose both All of the Above and None of the Above to solve.<n>All of the Above can meet the answer requirement, and None of the Aabove has no solution to meet.<n>Choices in colums E: All Of The Above or None Of The Above.<n>Choose both All Of The Above and None Of The Above since both choices meet the answer requirement.<n>Therefore, the final answer is: solar energy<n><n>Input: If 3 ≤ x < 5, what is the median between 2 and x?<n>Output: The median is x + 1, where 3 ≤ x, and this is between 2 and x.<n>Therefore, x + 1 < x < 5<n>So x is 4 and x + 1 is 5 <n>Hence, 4 < x < 5 and x + 1 > x where the median between 2 is 4 and x is 5.<n>So the median is x + 2 = 5 <n><n>Input: Is the number 127 square?<n>Output: No; 127 is not a square number. Choices: A: yes B: no<n>Hence, the number 126 is not a square number and the final answer is no.<n><n>Input: Is 200 the product of two prime numbers
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. Choices:  A: feel sorry B: trust god C: cross street D: ride a bike E: lend money<n>Output:		The options are either riding a bike (since it is implied 'if'), lend money (since it is also implied 'if'), trust God (not something a person can do or not do to hurt someone else) or cross the street(not something a person can choose/not choose to hurt anyone). So we can eliminate B,E,D,C.<n>A: does that mean doing something to hurt someone causes you do to feel sorry? No, it can't mean that. That would give rise to an infinite loop. So, A can't be the correct answer.<n>B: if you feel sorry for hurting the other person, does that mean you don't trust God? No, since if you trust God for everything, then that makes you feel guilty. So, it can't be an answer either.<n>D: riding a bike is just an act to cross the road and it doesn't have a feeling of the person who is hurt/hurts. So it can't be right.<n>C: This is also not true. Trusting God means we completely let God be responsible for things. So again it can't be the right answer.<n>So, if the correct answer is A and B can't be the answer. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:She was bad at dancing, so what basic skill did the instructor teach her? Choices:  A: eaten B: glassess C: jar D: pizza E: refrigerator<n>Output:		Olives should be put in the refrigerator.<n>The food will get wet in the refrigeration.<n>So the final choice is A: refrigerator.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. Choices: A: 125  B: 150  C: 174  D: 175  E: 200<n>Output: The width of the box is 6 feet which can be represented by 6/(12+1) = <<6*(1/12+1)>>6/12 which is 5/6 of the box.<n>The length of the box (6+5/6) is 6 + 3/2 = <<6+3/2=9>>9 feet.<n>Then we multiply the dimension with a conversion factor; 9 * (12 + 1) = <<9*(12+1)<n>>>176 inches and the total number will give us 176 + 5/6 * 125 inches = <<176+5/6*(125)>>775 inches.<n><n>So, the stadium can fit 9 = 775/775 = 1 persons in a box which is <<775/7=1<n>>><n><n>A final answer is 1 person can fit in a box<n><n>Input: There are 1256 students and they have a 49% chance of not participating in the fundraiser. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What is a great place to lay in the sun? Choices:  A: in the basement B: west C: solar system D: beach E: beans<n>Output:		The correct answers for the choices are A:basement; B:west; C:solar system; D:beach.<n><n><n>

Choices: A: 4 grandchildren B: 13 grandchildren C: 14 grandchildren D: 16 grandchildren E: 17 grandchildren <n>Output: The sum of all the Grandchildren is 13 + 12 + 11 + 10 + 9 + 5 = <<13+12+11+10+9+5=72>>72<n>Now the two missing grandchildren are 71 - 72 = <<71-72=1>>1.<n>Then the man has 1+72+1 = <<1+72+5=78>>78 grandchildren. <n>So the final answer should be 78<n><n>Input:There are 6 crows on a tree branch. How many crows remains on the tree branch? <n>Output: 2 + 4 = <<2+4=6>>6 crows are left on that branch.<n>The total number is 6 + 5 – 6 = <<6+5 -6=5>>5<n>So the final answer 5 or 6 (there is some choice for you to check)<n><n>Input: In every school, there is at least one teacher. There are five students who are not teachers, and there are 3 teachers. How many students are there in that school? Choices: A B : C D: E F: G<n>Output: The total students in the class are 1 + 2 + 3+ 4 + 5 = << 2 + 3 + 4 + 5>>5<n>The total teachers are 4 ( since there is student who are teachers in total that is why 4)<n>The number of teachers is 4 - 5 = << 4-5=1>>1<n>The total students are 5 - 1 = <<5-1=4>>4<n>So the final answer for this question is 4 or 5 (there is some choice to be checked)<n><n>Input: What is the 33-digit number that is obtained by adding: two
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:He was receiving workman's compensation, he had tripped over a metal rod while building where? Choices:  A: factory B: construction site C: engine D: insides of skyscraper's walls E: shops<n>Output:		He was receiving workmen's compensation because he tripped over a metal bar while building a engine.<n>There are many machines used in engines, therefore B is the correct answer.<n><n>### Conclusion:<n>The answer is 210

Choices:  A: feel cold B: feel pressure C: feel bumpy D: itches E: feel clammy<n>Output:		E: feel clammed<n>B: feel pressure<n>A: feel cold<n>C: feel bumpy<n>D: itches<n>So the final answer (The answer in the book)is C<n><n>**Sample input A:**<n>Input: There are three boxes of pizza, 12 slices in each box, how many slices of pizza are there overall?<n>Output: 36 slices of pizza<n>Note the boxes in the sample input A<n>**Sample input B:**<n>Input: Which of these animals is an omnivore? A: lion<n>B: cow<n>C: fox<n>D: bear<n>Output: C: fox<n>Note the animals in sample B<n>**Sample input C:**<n>Input: What will happen to skin pinch in something? Sam is 5 inches taller than Sara. How Tall are John and Sam? Sara has the height of <<3/2>>3/2 inches.<n>Output: John is <<3/2>>feet tall. Sam has <<5/2>>5/2 feet tall. So Sam is (2/3) feet tall. John has <<3/2>>2/3 of that height, so he is (3/5) feet tall.<n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:The new play was the go to performance of the year, all the crowds would stand and what? If the number is negative, subtract them for the square <n><n>Input:The sum of the first 4 even integers is the sum of the first 6 even integers.The sum of the first n even integers is sum of the first n + 1 even integers.How many even prime numbers were used to create this?<n>Output:Prime numbers are a number smaller than 1, with no factors other than the number 1. These are numbers divisible by all numbers above 1.<n><n>So, even numbers have to divisible by 2. But divisible by all numbers means divisible by 1, since 1 is considered to be a number. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What are you hoping to achieve when talking to someone? Choices:  A: communicating with others B: hurt feelings C: dry mouth D: intimacy E: changing behavior<n>Output:		Choices: A: communicate; B: hurt feelings; C:dry mouth;<n>D:intimacy; E: changing behavior<n>The answer is A, B, E, D, and E.<n>So the final answers are communication with others, hurt feelings, dry mouth, intimacy, and changing behavior<n><n>Input: How many different colors can make up a color scheme for a bedroom? Choices: 1. A: 2 colors B: 3 colors C: 4 colors  D: 8 colors E: 12 colors<n>Output: The minimum number of colors are 3.<n>The maximum number of colors are 12.<n>The answer is A: 2 colors, B: 3 colors, C: 4 colors, D: 8 colors and E: 12<n><n><n>#!/bin/python3<n>import unittest<n><n>class Solution:<n>    def totalDifferent(self, nums):<n>        unique = []<n>        for i in nums:<n>            if i in unique:<n>                continue<n>            unique.append(i)<n><n><n>        count_unique = len(unique)<n><n>        return count_unique<n><n>    def getMin(self,nums):<n>        res = min(nums) - 1<n><n>        return res<n><n><n>    def getMax(self,nums,max_value):<n>        for i in range(len(nums)):<n>            if not nums[i]:<n>                continue<n>            <n>            nums[i] -= 1<n>            <n>            temp = self.getMin(nums)<n>            if nums[i] < temp:<n>                res = i<n>                break<n><n>        return res + 1<n><n>    def isNanDuplicate(self,dup_nums):<n>        for i,num in enumerate(dup_nums): <n>            if not self.getMin(dup_nums) - 2 <= i < self.getMax(dup_nums,self.getMax(dup<n>            nums)):<n>                return False<n><n>        return True<n><n>        def isNANunique(nums):<n>            if self.isNanDuplicate (dup_nums): return False<n>            return True<n><n>        res = isNanunique(nums)<n>        return
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:If your watching television and accomplish nothing what have you done? Choices:  A: getting fat B: get fat C: typing words D: falling asleep E: wasted time<n>Output:		The answer is that you have accomplished nothing if you are watching tv and you are falling asleep<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:In the middle of the day what will someone do because of being hungry? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Where can peanut butter be stored? So the best answer is A and supermarket is the best choice.Because all the jars in supermarket are all the peanut butter jars.The A supermarket will be the best choice.<n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:John ran out of pencils. How much profit, if any, did you make?<n>Output: You made a profit of $36.50.<n>Let $x represent the original purchase price of the shoes.<n>We know that you sold them for less than $80, so $80 > x > $0. You spent $43.00 on some sort of shipping, so $x > $43.0.<n>Since $x represents the original purchase price of your shoes, then the total cost of the shoes was: $80 - x > $43.5.<n>Since $x > $4.5, $80 - x = $43.5, and so by addition, x - $4.50 = $43.<n><n>If x = $55 was your original purchase price, then the profit you made was $36.5 ($55 - $18.50).<n>So the final answer to $55 - $15.5 = $38.5<n><n>Input: There are no bats on a cold windy night. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:If done correctly grooming pet's nails generally does not cause this? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. The temperature, in degrees Fahrenheit, had dropped by 10 degrees since morning, which was at 5 a.m. The air temperature rose 10 degrees when it rained, but the ground temperature <n> dropped 5 degrees. If it was 9:27 pm when the rain was predicted for 6:55 pm, what was the air temperature when the rain started?<n>Output: Let x be the air temperature when rain started. When the rain started, the air temperature x-10 = <<x-10=x>>x dropped 10 degress.<n>Therefore, When the rain started, it was x = 9 + 10 = <<9+10=19>>19 degrees Fahrenheit<n>Therefore, x-10 = <x-10=19>19 = 19 - 10 = <19-10=9>>9 degrees Fahrenheit.<n>Hence, x was 9-10 = <<9-10=1>>1 degrees Fahrenheit<n>So, when the rain started, it is 1 degrees Fahrenheit. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What country has with the capital of Amsterdam has a Fortis bank? There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:After eating a dinner of uncooked chicken, what was felt by the poor man? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:John was stuck in his house. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What treatment might an old time doctor have tried to accomplish with leeches? How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. Choices C and D both mean mercy, so the difference between them is 2. Choices D and E mean empathy, so their difference is -2. D is next and closer, so its point total is 1+1-2=-1 point.<n>Choice E is the farthest from all A, B, C, and D, so its point value will be +2 points.<n>Therefore, the final answer is 1-2+2= <<1-2+2=>0>>0

How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:James lived in the top of a tall tower.  He could see clouds when he looked out his window.  Where might he live? Choices:  A: in books B: radio station C: city D: tower E: medieval castle<n>Output:		James was in a radio tower or city and so he lived in one of those places.<n>As you know that if the number of options is <4, then the answer would be <3,4,8,9>,<n>4 means that it could be any of the choices.<n><n>Input: A bus trip from New York to Chicago takes about 38 hours. What is the distance between New York and Chicago?<n>Output: Since the bus trip takes < 38 hours, that's how many hours it travels every hour. But they can't travel from 12 AM to 1 AM at the same time every hour.<n>In order to make sure that they move the same distance every hour, they need to have enough rest to make sure that they can start at the same time for the next trip.<n>If the bus travels 38 hours, it means that it has enough time to stay in both states for one hour.<n><n>That way, if the bus starts at noon in New York, it can get to Chicago at 1 PM, so to make sure that the bus gets to Chicago at 1, it needs one hour in New York and one hour in Chicago, so a total of 2 hours of rest.  If it leaves New York at noon, then it takes more than one hour, so it makes sense for it to travel 10 hours at the most.<n>But that doesn't account for any time it travels while it's in one of the states.<n>So it still takes 2 hours to go from New York to Chicago.<n><n>If you take 2 more hours in Chicago, and use 10 hours in New York, all of it adds up.<n>That means that we can't have <12,22,32,42,52,62,72> as the answer, so if you have other ideas about time zones in the US, it won't work out for this problem because those time zones don't line up together.<n><n>Instruction:Write a program to answer the following problems.<n>Input: Janet was at her grandma's house one week, but then flew to Florida the next week. She was at the beach each day for 3 hours and went home every evening. She was 18 years old and she spent 2 days with her brother at Disneyworld. How many days did

How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. Choices:  A: middle east B: asia minor C: asia D: provide meat E: balkan peninsula<n>Output:		There are four options for choice and each one consists of two letters, e.g. A:asia B:asia minor, etc.<n>This means that one has exactly two letters to start.<n>Next, this sequence gives a letter and a choice for four more consecutive choices.<n>Letters are not available, and a letter can be given only if the previous choice was not one: <n>    >>> if (letter in letterSequence) and lettersLeft == 0:<n>    >>>         print (letter, '-', choice, '=', letterSequence)<n>    >>> else:<n>    >>>         lettersLeft -= 1<n><n>    A-M=A,<n>    A-A=C,<n>    A-P=D,<n>    A-T=E<n>    B-A=B,<n>    B-E=E<n>    C-A=F<n>    D-A=G<n>    E-A=D<n>    F-S=J<n>    F-P=L<n>    F-P-S=J<n><n>    G-T=H<n>    H-L=N<n><n>    I-H=I<n>    I-L=U<n>    J-K=M<n>    K-S=P<n>    L-N=V<n>    M-I=Y<n>    N-V=Z<n>    P-T=T<n>    Q-I=Q<n>    Q-E=U<n>    R-H=(R, H)<n>    S-F=S<n>    U-O=U<n>    V-Q=V<n>    W-K=W<n>    X-Y=X<n>    Y-T=Y<n>    Z-X=Z<n>    R-S=R<n>    R-R=R<n><n>The total amount of letters must not exceed 10. <n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Johnny and bill fought over money.  Johnny wanted it to be over.  What might he choose to do? Choices:  A: control people B: settle everything C: buy food D: increase power E: kill bill<n>Output:		Johnny needed the money to pay his rent and bill has been cheating him.<n>So,Johnny settled everything and paid his rent.<n>So the final choice is A: control people

How many spelling bee rounds did the whole group have?<n>Output: As they were all a group, there were 25 rounds.<n>Alicia made it 25 - 10 = <<25-10=15>>15 less rounds than the whole group.<n>Therefore, the final answer is 15 rounds<n><n>Input: A car and a motorcycle race from point A to point B, 100 feet apart. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:The new kitten hadn't gotten used to what it was allowed to climb on in most rooms, so the owned kept the bedroom door what? Choices:  A: opened B: closed C: found at shower D: falling down E: locked<n>Output:		The correct answer is C.<n>Finding the answer using the first clued : <n>What was the kitten allowed to climb on: <n> Clues of choices: <n>1. Opened = Bedroom door was opened, the kitten can go in <n>2. Closed = Bedroom door was closed, the kitten can not go in<n>3. Falling down = Showers is not suitable for climbing,so the kitten would fell down<n>4. Locked = Can the kitten go out <n>Therefore,the correct answer is C.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What is a place where you usually store dishes but not books? Choices:  A: apartment B: pantry C: table D: living room E: shelf<n>Output:		The word pantry only occurs in the sentences.<n><n>Input:The total sum of 2 sets is 230. Set1 contains 20 less than set2. If set1 contains 80, how many objects are in set1?<n>Output: The total of set1 + set2 = (230 - 80) = <<230-80=150>>150.<n>Therefore, set1 is (150 - 20) so there are (150 -20) - 80 = (70 - 80)=<<70-80=>-10>>-10 objects in set1.<n>So the final answe is 70<n><n># Part B #<n>## Solution:<n>#### Answer: <n>**Time Complexity** : O(N),<n>**Space complexity**: O(N)<n><n><n>#### Solution<n>**Time Complexity:** O(N)<n>**Space Complexity:** O()<n><n>```python<n># Definition for a binary tree node.<n>class TreeNode:<n>    def __init__(self, val=0, left=None, right=None):<n>        self.val = val<n>        self.left = left<n>        self.right = right<n><n>class Solution:<n>    def levelOrder(self, root: TreeNode) -> List[List[float]]:<n>        """<n>        Time complexity: O(N) where N is a length of the tree.<n>        Space complexity: O()<n>        """<n>        result = []<n><n>        def helper(root, lst):<n>            if not root: return<n>            for i in range(len(root.left)):<n>                helper(root.left[i], lst)<n>            lst.append(root.val)<n>            for i in list(range(len(root.right),-1, -1)):<n>                helper(node=root.right[i],lst=lst)<n><n>        helper(root=root,lst=result) <n>        for i, val in enumerate(result):<n>            result[i].append(val)<n><n>        return result<n>```<n><n><n><n>### Instruction:Answer the instruction correctly.<n><n>input: A 6m 130cm long piece o a rope is cut and returned to

How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:The woman experienced great joy, but despite that this was a what? What is the total number of prices in the store?<n>Output: The total number of prices in a store is 22 + (22 + 4) = <<22+22+4=58>>58.<n>From this we can subtract 17 = <<58-17=41>>41 prices for meat, fish an poultry.<n>So, the total number of prices is 41 + 29 = <<41+29= 70>>70.<n>Therefore, the final answer is 70<n><n>Input: A store was selling a shelf to a customer for 10% less than the previous selling price, which was 22% higher than the original price. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. Choices:  A: new experiences B: playfulness C: own house D: good looking E: beautiful<n>Output:		An outgoing person is likely to seek experiences or fun.<n>If you are more outgoing, you will enjoy many things.<n>A outgoing person seeks what: new experience or fun.<n>B outgoing person seeks: new experience or fun, playfulness is not outgoing.<n>C outgoing person seeks : new experience or fun, good looking is in the wrong place.<n>D outgoing person seeks new experience or fun. So the final answer is A <n><n>Input:If they are quiet what are they likely to do? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Sarah took poison by accident She found it in the cabinet and. thought that it was what? How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Where would a human expect to find manufacturing operations? Choices:  A: factory B: school C: grocery store D: band E: aircraft<n>Output:		Manufacturing operations would not be found in a school. How many computers were upgraded?<n>Output: There were 21 computers initially, so we subtract 21 from the number of computers with new software. The computers chosen are called the pool. This pool is of size k which is the number of pooled computers.<n>To do this, we multiply k times the number of computers chosen for the pool in step 0. The new software will be delivered to all of the pool computers. So we calculate the total number of computers that have new software.<n>Output: There are always k + 1 ways to distribute the pool and since all computers eventually get new software, the question states every computer has new software which is the same, so we add 1 to everything and calculate the total number of ways to distribute the computer pool. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. What was the width of the rectangular box?<n>Output:A rectangular box of width x and length x = 5 feet x 15 feet.<n>Therefore, the width of the new rectangular box is: sqrt(10² + 10² + 2 x²) = 10<n>So the final answer the width of the new box is 10 feet.<n><n>Input: There are 8 boys and 14 girls in Mrs. Andersons class. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:If you're standing in line and the line isn't moving what might you feel? Choices:  A: order B: queueing up C: wait turn D: fatigue E: anger<n>Output:		A: I'd feel order since  I'm standing in line and I might waiting for the food of the restaurant. I feel bored because of queueing for nothing, waiting for turn, and fatigue that I feel in wait turn. Choices A and E are the correct answer. So the final answer is A and E<n><n>Note: If the answer is A and E then the answer is A and B too.<n><n>#### 10<n><n>Input: A number has an even number of digits and the sum of the digit in the hundreds, tens, and ones places is less than 100. How many digits can a number have that contains 40?<n>Output: A number can have 40 digits.<n>Since a number has an even number, the number has 20 digits. The sum of the digits in the hundreds, tens and ones places is less then 100. This sum is 40, 20 x 2 = 40 and 20 + 20 - 20. So the final answer 20 digits<n><n>Output: You have 100 or less 10-digit numbers with distinct digits.<n>The answer is 180 since if a number have 9 digits, there are only 4 possibility. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What would a person do if he or she just woke up? Choices:  A: drink tea B: thank god C: open eyes D: feel angry E: complete sentence<n>Output:		The person will complete the sentence <<'The sun...'><n>Since a person who woke up would be half awake that's why the answer must be 'E'. And that's why the final answer is E.<n><n>Input: How much sugar does a box of blueberry muffins contain? Choices: 1 B: 2 C: 3 D: 5 E: more than the muffins<n>Output: The box of blueberry munchins contains <<'Munchins contain...'><n>Since a box of blueberry contains munchin's so that's why the only choice is 'D'. <n>So the final answer will be D.<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What are people playing when they want to take the lead with small papers? Choices:  A: very heavy B: video game C: news article D: card game E: lead pencil<n>Output:		You will know you are taking the lead when your partner holds a small paper in his hand. This kind of is a card game. Choice "D: card game", is the final answer.<n><n>Input: The first step in solving a problem is__________.<n>Output: It is to define the problem.  Choice "A. understand the problem" is the final answer.

How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:What do you fill with ink to print? If the units digit is greater than the tens digit, then subtract 9. If the tens digit is greater than the units digit, then subtract 4. If the tens digit equals the units digit, the sum is negative. Example: 12 + 57 = 7 (sum) (The units digit is 1, so the units digit plus 1/2(the tens digit)+16=1+2+16=19). If the units digit is 2, then we subtract 9(9–2). If the tens digit is 2, the we subtract 4(2-4=0). If the units digit and the tens<n>Output: digit are the same, then the sum is negative. The units digit of 422863579 is 4. So the sum is -16586357(negative). When you find the last digit in a three digit number, add one, double the second digit and add three to the sum. If it is less than ten, then subtract ten, and if it is greater, then subtract 5. Example: 77 + 24 = 44 (adding 1, 2 doubles to 24=48, substracting 10). If the sum is less than 24 then you add 24 and repeat step 9.<n>So if the sum is less than, than 24 add 24 and go back to step 10<n>The units digit of 437672908 is 7. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:She was processing the wool, she kept her leg bouncing to operate the what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:When going to sleep what noise does a human make? To do that we should know what multiple choice question is, and how it can be solved. So, there are two types of multiple choice questions i) 1st type of MCQ is to select the option whose answer is true for the specific set of given variables. ii) The 2nd type of MCQ is, to find the value whose sign is correct according to the given data in the question. Let us assume for the example that we want to answer the following multiple choice question <n>	<n>```math<n>Ask Question:<n>Choose all that apply. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. He rode the bus 20 blocks to the post office to get some stamps. Later, he came home the same way. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:To gain her trust the real estate agent was very polite, delightful and all around what? She really made all around what people called being polite and delightful (Choice:C) to the people who would come to the open house.<n>So the final answers are C,D<n>Input: John needs to send a money order to his brother for his birthday. How much money should John send in the envelope in order to send his brother the exact amount of money?<n><n>Output:John needs to know how much he needs to send, to send his brother the right amount of money. So lets multiply $5 (cost to send money order) by 5 since it weighs 5 dollars (1.5 ounci x 3.5 ounces to make a dollar) times 5 dollars it comes out to be $97. This is the right amount of money he needs to send in the envelope. So the final answer is $97<n><n>Input: Alyssa has 5 boxes of cereal. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda. Mara has twice as many cards as Janet. How many cards do they have in all if Mara has 40 cards less than 150?<n>Output: Mara has 150 - 40 = <<150-40=110>>110 cards.<n>Janet has 110/2 = <<110/2=55>>55 cards since Mara has twice as many as Janet.<n>Brenda has 55 - 9 = <<55-9=46>>46 cards since Janet has 9 cards more than Brenda.<n>Therefore, they all have 110 + 55 + 46 = <<110+55+46=211>>211 cards.<n>So the final answer is 211<n><n>Input: Pete walked 5 blocks from his house to the bus garage in Houston. How many blocks did Pete travel in all?<n>Output: The number of blocks traveled on the way to the post office was 5 + 20 = <<5+20=25>>25.<n>Pete traveled 25 × 2 = <<25*2=50>>50 blocks in all.<n>So the final answer is 50<n><n>Input: In a classroom, there are blue chairs, green chairs, and white chairs. There are 10 blue chairs. The green chairs are 3 times as many as the blue chairs, and there are 13 fewer white chairs than the green and blue chairs combined. How many chairs are there in a classroom?<n>Output: There are 10 x 3 = <<10*3=30>>30 green chairs.<n>The total number of blue and green chairs is 10 + 30 = <<10+30=40>>40.<n>So, there are 40 - 13 = <<40-13=27>>27 white chairs.<n>Therefore, there are 40 +27 = <<40+27=67>>67 chairs in a classroom.<n>So the final answer is 67<n><n>Input:Remembering past successe is likely to cause what? How much farther in every direction can I travel?<n>Output: The distance from Earth to Boston is <<Earth to Boston>>1050 miles.<n>The distance from Earth to the moon is 238,856 miles.<n>The distance to lightning during an average day is 0.6 miles.<n>The time to get to Chicago is about 15 hours, so the average speed is about 67 miles per hour.<n>So, the distance from the Earth to Chicago would equal <<Earth to Chicago>>1050 - <1050*(67/15)=850>>850 miles.<n>So the final distance is 1050 + 850 = <<1050+850=1850>>1850 miles in every direction I can travel.<n>So the final output is 1850<n>
